---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
export const prerender = true;
---
<Base title="What is ai.txt? The Complete Guide (2025)" description="The definitive guide to ai.txt — the emerging standard for declaring AI usage policies. Format spec, real examples, comparison with TDM headers, and implementation checklist.">
  <article class="learn-page">
    <div class="container content">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a> / <a href="/learn/ai-txt">Learn</a> / <span>ai.txt</span>
      </nav>

      <h1>What is ai.txt? The Complete Guide <span class="badge experimental">Experimental</span></h1>
      <p class="lead">
        <strong>ai.txt</strong> is an emerging proposal for declaring your website's AI usage policies.
        While robots.txt controls <em>access</em>, ai.txt communicates <em>intent</em> — how you want
        AI companies to use (or not use) your content. It's the difference between locking your door
        and posting terms of the lease.
      </p>

      <div class="notice">
        <strong>Status:</strong> ai.txt is not yet a widely adopted standard. It's an experimental
        proposal being explored by the web community. We track it because it represents an
        important trend toward explicit AI content governance. Treat it as a declaration of intent,
        not a technical enforcement mechanism.
      </div>

      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2 class="toc-title">On this page</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="#why">Why ai.txt matters</a></li>
          <li><a href="#format">The format (full spec)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#examples">Real-world examples</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">ai.txt vs other standards</a></li>
          <li><a href="#best-practices">Best practices</a></li>
          <li><a href="#adoption">Adoption status</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
          <li><a href="#implementation">Implementation checklist</a></li>
        </ul>
      </nav>

      <!-- ─── Why ─── -->
      <section id="why">
        <h2>Why ai.txt matters</h2>
        <p>
          The web has a content licensing problem. AI companies crawl billions of pages to train models,
          but website owners have no standard way to say "you can use my content for search, but not
          for training." robots.txt was designed for a simpler era — it controls which paths a bot can
          access, but says nothing about <em>what the bot does with the content after fetching it</em>.
        </p>
        <p>ai.txt exists to fill that gap. Here's why it matters:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Express nuanced consent.</strong> robots.txt is binary: allow or block. ai.txt lets you say "search yes, training no, attribution required." This mirrors how real content licensing works.</li>
          <li><strong>Legal defensibility.</strong> As AI copyright cases move through courts (NYT v. OpenAI, Getty v. Stability AI), having an explicit, machine-readable policy statement strengthens your legal position. It's harder for a company to claim "we didn't know" when you published a clear policy file.</li>
          <li><strong>Complement robots.txt.</strong> You might <em>want</em> GPTBot to access your content (so ChatGPT can answer questions about your product) but not use it for model training. robots.txt can't express this. ai.txt can.</li>
          <li><strong>Future-proof governance.</strong> The EU AI Act, US copyright legislation, and other regulatory frameworks are increasingly requiring transparency about training data. ai.txt provides a standardized way to declare your stance before regulation forces the issue.</li>
          <li><strong>Signal to the ecosystem.</strong> Even if no AI company checks ai.txt today, publishing one signals to your users, legal team, and the broader community that you've thought about AI policy. It's a public commitment.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Format ─── -->
      <section id="format">
        <h2>The format (full spec)</h2>
        <p>
          Place a plain-text file at <code>/ai.txt</code> on your domain root. The format uses simple
          key-value pairs, one per line. Comments start with <code>#</code>. Fields can repeat.
        </p>

        <h3>Annotated example</h3>
        <pre><code># AI Policy for example.com
# Last updated: 2025-01-15

# Human-readable policy statements (repeat as needed)
Policy: Allow AI-powered search and summarization of public content
Policy: Require attribution when generating content based on our material
Policy: Disallow use of content for model training or fine-tuning
Policy: User-generated content may not be used for any AI purpose

# Contact for AI usage inquiries
Contact: ai-policy@example.com
Contact: https://example.com/ai-policy

# What AI uses are acceptable
Preferred-Model-Use: search, summarization, question-answering, citation

# What AI uses are prohibited
Disallowed-Model-Use: training, fine-tuning, embedding-generation, synthetic-data

# License governing AI usage (SPDX identifier)
License: CC-BY-NC-4.0

# Link to full legal policy
Terms: https://example.com/terms#ai-usage

# Paths with specific policies (experimental)
Path: /docs/*
Path-Policy: Allow training with attribution
Path: /blog/*
Path-Policy: Disallow training
Path: /api/*
Path-Policy: No AI usage permitted</code></pre>

        <h3>Complete field reference</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Field</th><th>Required</th><th>Repeatable</th><th>Description</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>Policy</code></td>
              <td>Recommended</td>
              <td>Yes</td>
              <td>A human-readable policy statement. Use plain language. Each statement should cover one specific rule.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>Contact</code></td>
              <td>Recommended</td>
              <td>Yes</td>
              <td>Email address or URL for AI usage inquiries. Allows AI companies to reach you with questions or licensing requests.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>Preferred-Model-Use</code></td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>Comma-separated list of acceptable AI uses. Common values: <code>search</code>, <code>summarization</code>, <code>question-answering</code>, <code>citation</code>, <code>translation</code>.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>Disallowed-Model-Use</code></td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>Comma-separated list of prohibited AI uses. Common values: <code>training</code>, <code>fine-tuning</code>, <code>embedding-generation</code>, <code>synthetic-data</code>, <code>image-generation</code>.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>License</code></td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>SPDX license identifier governing AI usage. Examples: <code>CC-BY-4.0</code>, <code>CC-BY-NC-4.0</code>, <code>CC-BY-SA-4.0</code>, <code>All-Rights-Reserved</code>.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>Terms</code></td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>URL to your full AI usage policy or Terms of Service section covering AI.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>Path</code></td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>Yes</td>
              <td>URL path pattern with glob support. Applies the subsequent <code>Path-Policy</code> to matching URLs.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>Path-Policy</code></td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>Yes</td>
              <td>Policy statement for the preceding <code>Path</code>. Allows per-section granularity.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Examples ─── -->
      <section id="examples">
        <h2>Real-world examples</h2>
        <p>Here's what ai.txt looks like for different types of websites:</p>

        <h3>News publisher (restrictive)</h3>
        <p>A major news outlet that wants AI to surface their articles in search but not use them for training:</p>
        <pre><code># AI Policy for dailynews.com
# Our journalism is not training data.

Policy: AI-powered search and citation with attribution is permitted
Policy: Model training and fine-tuning on our content is prohibited
Policy: Synthetic content generation mimicking our editorial voice is prohibited
Policy: Summarization must link to the original article

Contact: legal@dailynews.com
Terms: https://dailynews.com/terms/ai

Preferred-Model-Use: search, citation
Disallowed-Model-Use: training, fine-tuning, synthetic-data, voice-cloning

License: All-Rights-Reserved

Path: /wire/*
Path-Policy: Licensed from AP/Reuters — no AI use without separate license</code></pre>

        <h3>Open-source project (permissive)</h3>
        <p>An OSS documentation site that welcomes all AI usage with attribution:</p>
        <pre><code># AI Policy for openlib.dev
# We build in the open. Use our docs freely.

Policy: All content is available for AI training and inference
Policy: Attribution appreciated but not required for training
Policy: Generated code examples from our docs may be used freely

Contact: hello@openlib.dev
Terms: https://openlib.dev/license

Preferred-Model-Use: training, fine-tuning, search, summarization, code-generation
License: MIT</code></pre>

        <h3>E-commerce site (mixed policies)</h3>
        <p>An online store with different policies for different content types:</p>
        <pre><code># AI Policy for shopexample.com

Policy: Product descriptions may be used for search and comparison
Policy: Customer reviews may not be used for any AI purpose
Policy: Product images may not be used for image generation training

Contact: partnerships@shopexample.com

Preferred-Model-Use: search, price-comparison, product-recommendation
Disallowed-Model-Use: training, image-generation, review-synthesis

Path: /products/*
Path-Policy: Allow search and summarization
Path: /reviews/*
Path-Policy: No AI usage — user-generated content
Path: /images/*
Path-Policy: No training or generation usage</code></pre>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Comparison ─── -->
      <section id="comparison">
        <h2>ai.txt vs other standards</h2>
        <p>
          ai.txt isn't the only approach to AI content governance. Here's how it compares to
          existing and emerging standards:
        </p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Standard</th><th>What it does</th><th>Enforcement</th><th>AI-specific?</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>robots.txt</strong></td>
              <td>Controls crawler access to paths (allow/block)</td>
              <td>Technical — bots are expected to check</td>
              <td>No (but AI bots should respect it)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>ai.txt</strong></td>
              <td>Declares usage policies (how content may be used)</td>
              <td>Legal/social — policy declaration</td>
              <td>Yes — built for AI governance</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>llms.txt</strong></td>
              <td>Provides structured context (what the site is about)</td>
              <td>Informational — helps AI understand</td>
              <td>Yes — built for LLMs</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>TDM headers</strong> (EU)</td>
              <td>HTTP header <code>TDM-Reservation: 1</code> to opt out of text/data mining</td>
              <td>Legal — backed by EU DSM Directive Art. 4</td>
              <td>Partially — covers data mining broadly</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>C2PA metadata</strong></td>
              <td>Embeds provenance data in media files (who created it, how)</td>
              <td>Technical — verifiable chain of trust</td>
              <td>Partially — AI-generated content labeling</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Creative Commons</strong></td>
              <td>Standardized content licenses (CC-BY, CC-NC, etc.)</td>
              <td>Legal — well-established case law</td>
              <td>No — predates AI, but applies</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
          <strong>Key insight:</strong> These standards are complementary, not competing. Use robots.txt
          for access control, ai.txt for usage policy, llms.txt for AI context, and TDM headers for
          EU compliance. A comprehensive AI governance setup uses all of them.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Best Practices ─── -->
      <section id="best-practices">
        <h2>Best practices</h2>
        <div class="practices-grid">
          <div class="do-col">
            <h3>Do</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Be specific about what you allow and prohibit — "no training" is clearer than "limited AI use"</li>
              <li>Include a contact email so AI companies can reach you with licensing questions</li>
              <li>Reference your Terms of Service or a dedicated AI policy page via the <code>Terms</code> field</li>
              <li>Use ai.txt <em>alongside</em> robots.txt — they serve different purposes</li>
              <li>Use per-path policies when different content types have different rules</li>
              <li>Update your ai.txt when your policies change (and note the date in a comment)</li>
              <li>Use standard SPDX license identifiers when specifying a <code>License</code></li>
              <li>Consider your users' content separately — UGC often needs stricter policies</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="dont-col">
            <h3>Don't</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Don't rely on ai.txt as your only defense — it's a policy declaration, not a technical block</li>
              <li>Don't use vague language like "reasonable use" — be concrete about permitted and prohibited uses</li>
              <li>Don't forget to also configure robots.txt if you want to technically block AI crawlers</li>
              <li>Don't assume all AI companies check ai.txt yet — adoption is still early</li>
              <li>Don't contradict your robots.txt — if you block a bot in robots.txt but allow it in ai.txt, the block takes precedence</li>
              <li>Don't copy-paste an ai.txt without customizing it for your site's actual policies</li>
              <li>Don't set policies you can't or won't enforce — it weakens the standard for everyone</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Adoption ─── -->
      <section id="adoption">
        <h2>Adoption status</h2>
        <p>
          An honest assessment of where ai.txt stands today:
        </p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Status</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Specification</strong></td>
              <td>Community proposal — no formal RFC or W3C standard yet</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Publisher adoption</strong></td>
              <td>Early. Mostly tech-forward publishers and open-source projects experimenting with it</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>AI company support</strong></td>
              <td>No major AI company has committed to checking ai.txt yet. This is the biggest gap.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Legal standing</strong></td>
              <td>Untested in court. However, having an explicit policy file strengthens "willful infringement" arguments.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Tooling</strong></td>
              <td>Growing — scanners like llmstxt.codes detect and parse ai.txt. Generators are available.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Related momentum</strong></td>
              <td>TDM headers (EU), C2PA (media), and robots.txt AI extensions are moving faster with institutional backing.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
          <strong>Our recommendation:</strong> Add an ai.txt now. It takes 5 minutes, costs nothing, and
          establishes a clear public record of your AI policy. Even if enforcement is years away, the
          declaration itself has value — legally, socially, and as organizational policy documentation.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── FAQ ─── -->
      <section id="faq">
        <h2>FAQ</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is ai.txt legally binding?</h3>
          <p>
            Not by itself. ai.txt is a policy declaration, not a contract. However, it can strengthen
            legal arguments by demonstrating that you clearly communicated your terms. Courts in copyright
            cases look at whether the infringer had notice — a published ai.txt is strong evidence of notice.
            For binding enforcement, pair it with your Terms of Service.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Does anyone actually check ai.txt?</h3>
          <p>
            Not yet at scale. No major AI company has publicly committed to checking ai.txt. However,
            the same was true of robots.txt in its early years. The standard gains power through adoption —
            the more sites publish ai.txt, the more pressure AI companies face to respect it. Tools like
            llmstxt.codes already parse it, and awareness is growing.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How does ai.txt differ from robots.txt?</h3>
          <p>
            robots.txt controls <strong>access</strong> — which bots can fetch which pages. ai.txt controls
            <strong>usage</strong> — what bots can do with the content after fetching it. You might allow
            GPTBot to crawl your docs (robots.txt: allow) but prohibit using them for model training
            (ai.txt: disallowed). They're complementary, not competing.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Should I have both robots.txt and ai.txt?</h3>
          <p>
            Yes. robots.txt is the technical enforcement layer (bots are expected to obey it). ai.txt is
            the policy layer (declaring what you permit). Think of robots.txt as the lock on your door and
            ai.txt as the terms of your lease. Both are valuable; neither replaces the other.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What if my ai.txt contradicts my robots.txt?</h3>
          <p>
            robots.txt takes technical precedence. If you block a bot in robots.txt, it shouldn't fetch
            your content at all — making your ai.txt policies moot for that bot. If you allow a bot in
            robots.txt but restrict usage in ai.txt, the bot <em>should</em> follow the ai.txt usage
            restrictions (but there's no technical enforcement today). Best practice: keep them consistent.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Will AI companies eventually respect ai.txt?</h3>
          <p>
            The trend points toward yes. Regulatory pressure (EU AI Act, US copyright cases), publisher
            pushback, and industry self-regulation are all moving toward more granular consent mechanisms.
            Google, OpenAI, and Anthropic already respect robots.txt directives for their AI crawlers.
            A standard for usage policy (which ai.txt aims to be) is a natural next step.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What content type should ai.txt be served with?</h3>
          <p>
            Serve it as <code>text/plain; charset=utf-8</code>. It should be a static file at the root
            of your domain: <code>https://yourdomain.com/ai.txt</code>. No HTML, no JSON — just
            plain text with key-value pairs.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Checklist ─── -->
      <section id="implementation">
        <h2>Implementation checklist</h2>
        <ul class="checklist">
          <li>Define your AI usage policy — what do you allow, what do you prohibit?</li>
          <li>Create a plain-text file at <code>/ai.txt</code> on your domain root</li>
          <li>Add <code>Policy</code> statements covering your key rules</li>
          <li>Add a <code>Contact</code> email or URL for AI usage inquiries</li>
          <li>Specify <code>Preferred-Model-Use</code> and <code>Disallowed-Model-Use</code></li>
          <li>Add a <code>License</code> field with an SPDX identifier if applicable</li>
          <li>Link to your full Terms of Service via the <code>Terms</code> field</li>
          <li>Add per-path policies if different content types need different rules</li>
          <li>Verify it's accessible: <code>curl -I https://yourdomain.com/ai.txt</code></li>
          <li>Ensure your robots.txt and ai.txt don't contradict each other</li>
          <li>Add a date comment so you know when it was last updated</li>
          <li>Scan your site to verify detection: <a href="/">llmstxt.codes scanner</a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <div class="cta-box">
        <h3>Check your site's AI policy</h3>
        <p>See if you have an ai.txt and how it factors into your AI readiness score.</p>
        <a href="/" class="action-btn action-btn-primary">Scan your domain</a>
        <a href="/tools/generator/ai-txt" class="action-btn action-btn-secondary">Generate ai.txt</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .learn-page { padding: var(--space-8) 0 var(--space-16); }
  .content { max-width: var(--content-width); }
  .breadcrumb { font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: var(--space-6); }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--color-text-secondary); }

  h1 { font-size: var(--text-3xl); font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: var(--space-4); display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3); flex-wrap: wrap; }
